title: For Sale:  Husqvarna/Browning 380
postcontent: Husqvarna/ Browning Model 1907 in caliber .380ACP. These pistols were based on the Browning M1903 and were the standard military sidearm of Sweden during WW1 and also WW2, originally manufactured to fire the Browning 9x20MM Long. They were later easily modified by the US importer to shoot the more common .380ACP, known in Europe as the 9MM Kurtz/ Corto/ or Short. This particular pistol is in excellent condition, manufactured about 1930 with inspector Gustaf Bjorkenstam's initials under the royal crown and serial numbers identify it as being assigned to the 6th Infantry Regiment. The barrel is shiny, appears to be practically unfired and comes with the original military holster, three magazines, lanyard and cleaning rod. Recoil spring and magazine springs are still very strong and the pistol will fire the .380 without fail.

postcontent: WWII/Korean War M3 Carbine, Inland, sn64xxxxx (August 1944) with Infrared Scope, switch handle, and Transit Box. It is my understanding that this model was indeed used at the very end of WWII, but they were very present through out the Korean War. Verification of correct part types and markings was done using the following references: 1) M1 Carbine by R.C. Larson (the best single resource by far!); 2) The M1 Carbine III, by J.C. Harrison; and 3) U.S. M1 Carbines, Wartime Production, by Craig Reisch. There are also the ubiquitous War Baby tones by Ruth (volumes I, II & III), but they are mostly history, excessively detailed and hard to use as a collector's tool. This carbine is a shooter, with M2 stock, and M3 hand guard, all parts are correct types for build month and year and date of acceptance by the military. All parts are correct for the manufacturer. The rifle comes with a 30rd mag. Barrel is the original with good ME and TE measurements, the bore is shiney and free from any pitting and frost. Original stock, hardware and finish. This rifle has been fully carefully maintained and comes ready to shoot. The Stock has the original type finish. All parts have their original finish, but wear from use during war time, as well as peace, is evident on all painted parts. CONDITION: Used/ Fully restored/ well maintained good condition. Crisp mechanics, correct military finish. Both surplus military rounds and modern Hornady ammunition have been fired through the rifle with full reliability and accuracy. This rifle is an old war horse and should be respected as such. If you know anything about this gun, you know how rare this combo is
